3:["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["How Funding Works on ","Binance"]}]
4:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Binance calculates SEI/USDT funding rates using the Interest Rate (0.01% daily) and Premium Index, which measures the difference between perpetual contract price and mark price. The funding rate is capped at ±0.375% per 8-hour period to prevent extreme payments. Long positions pay funding when rates are positive, while short positions pay when negative, with settlements occurring automatically in your USDT balance. Binance's mark price uses a weighted average of major spot exchanges to minimize manipulation and ensure fair funding calculations."}]
5:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SEI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SEI's focus on trading infrastructure creates distinct funding rate patterns compared to other L1 tokens, particularly during DeFi market cycles and exchange integrations. The pair maintains moderate volatility with sufficient volume for meaningful arbitrage positions without significant slippage. SEI's correlation with broader DeFi trends often creates predictable funding rate cycles that experienced arbitrageurs can capitalize on."}]]}]
6:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SEI/USDT funding rates on Binance typically range from -0.1% to +0.2% per 8-hour period, with extreme rates reaching ±0.375% during major network updates or partnership announcements. The pair shows strong correlation with DeFi sector performance, often maintaining positive funding during bull markets as traders position for ecosystem growth. Weekend periods frequently show reduced funding volatility due to lower retail participation, creating more stable arbitrage conditions. Historical data indicates funding rate reversals often occur around major SEI ecosystem milestones, providing timing opportunities for strategic position entries."}]]}]
7:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Strategies"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage between Binance and other platforms trading SEI perpetuals can yield 0.05-0.3% per funding period when rate differentials emerge. Delta-neutral strategies work effectively with SEI due to moderate spot-futures basis relationships and sufficient options liquidity for hedging. Market makers benefit from SEI's predictable funding patterns around ecosystem announcements, allowing for strategic inventory positioning. The 8-hour funding intervals provide sufficient time for position adjustments, while Binance's API supports automated funding rate monitoring and execution strategies."}]]}]
8:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SEI's relatively low market cap compared to major cryptocurrencies increases funding rate volatility during significant price movements or low liquidity periods. Position sizing should account for potential gaps during network upgrades or major ecosystem changes that can impact funding calculations. Binance's insurance fund provides protection against extreme scenarios, but traders should monitor SEI's circulating supply changes that could affect perpetual contract dynamics. Consider correlation risks with other DeFi tokens in your portfolio, as SEI funding rates often move in tandem with sector-wide sentiment shifts affecting multiple positions simultaneously."}]]}]
9:["$","$Le",null,{"items":[{"question":"What are typical SEI/USDT funding rates on Binance?","answer":"SEI/USDT funding rates typically range from -0.1% to +0.2% per 8-hour period on Binance, with a maximum cap of ±0.375%. Rates tend to be positive during DeFi bull markets and can turn negative during sector corrections or broader crypto downturns."},{"question":"How does SEI's blockchain focus affect funding rates?","answer":"SEI's specialization in trading infrastructure creates funding rate patterns that correlate with DeFi adoption cycles and exchange integrations. Major ecosystem developments or partnership announcements often drive temporary funding rate spikes as traders position for potential price movements."},{"question":"What's the minimum position size for SEI funding arbitrage?","answer":"Binance requires a minimum order value of 5 USDT for SEI/USDT perpetuals, but practical arbitrage strategies typically require positions of at least 1,000 USDT to overcome trading fees and generate meaningful returns from funding rate differentials."},{"question":"How reliable is SEI liquidity for large arbitrage positions?","answer":"SEI/USDT maintains moderate liquidity on Binance with typical spreads of 0.01-0.03% during active hours. For positions above 50,000 USDT, monitor order book depth carefully as slippage can erode arbitrage profits, especially during low-volume Asian trading sessions."}]}]
